_ Look at the summary, I saw that many columns such as X, Year, State, Institution, course_type, gender,

  • Xs Max showed the total numbers of students in the dataset which are 128967 students
  • Year: show the period of time that students commencing from 2005 to 2017.
  • Institution: There are 6 institutions that have the most students which are Monash Uni, The University of Sydney, UNSW, University of Melbourne, Queensland University of Technology and University of Queenlands(more than 5000 students).
  • Course_type: show the type of degree that students chose to study. The highest one is Bachelor and Master Degree (82588 and 19437)
  • perm_home_country showed the most 5 countries having the most students registered to study in Australia: China, Malaysia, India and Hongkong, other

However, there are some variables having missing values in the dataset such as mceetya_regional_remote_count, asgs_regional_remote_count, onshore_indicator regionalremote_value, Regional, . To be specific, ATAR column has some missing values, I would examine it right away.

Which Insitution have the highest profit?

library(ggplot2)
insti.tb <- table(df$Institution)
insti.tb_df <- as.data.frame(insti.tb)
colnames(insti.tb_df) <- c("Institution", "Count")
insti.tb_df <- transform(insti.tb_df, Institution = reorder(Institution, Count))

insti.bar <- ggplot(insti.tb_df)+ geom_bar(aes(x=Institution,y= Count), stat="identity",
fill="gray") + 
coord_flip() +
labs(title = "Students per Institution", x = "Insitution", y = "Number of students") +
theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
theme(axis.text.y=element_text(size=rel(0.8)))

insti.bar

The bar showed the numbers of students registered to study in 41 institutions in Austrlia. As we saw that, there are 7 institutions which have more than 5000 students: UNSW, The Univeristy of Sydney, The Univeristy of Queensland, The Univeristy of Melbourne, Queensland University of Technology, Monash Univeristy and Deakin University.Most students choose to study in univeristies from Go8 University. So Monash has the highest number of students (6500) that leads to the highest profit.

Why Universities in Austrlia focus on developing Undergraduate, Postgraduate Coursework Program?

library(gridExtra)

bd.course_count <- ggplot(data = df) + 
geom_count(mapping = aes(x = age, y = broad_course_type)) +
labs(title = "Number of Students base on Broad Course Type at each Age Group", x = "Age", y = "Broad Course Type") +
theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = rel(0.8))) +
  coord_flip()

bd.overseas <- ggplot(df) + geom_bar(aes(x = broad_course_type, fill = overseas),position = "dodge") + 
labs(title = "Students per Broad Course Type base on Overseas", x = "Broad Course Type", y = "Number of student") +
theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 1)) +
  coord_flip()

grid.arrange(bd.course_count, bd.overseas, ncol=1)

Due to the graph above, Undergraduate has most students from 17 to 24 (above 7500 at each age). In addition, Postgraduate Coursework has most students from 30-39 to 40-49 (7500 and 5000). Besides, 30-39 is the age group Higher Degree Research has most (5000).Moreover, Postgraduate Coursework doesnt have student in 16 and under, and Higher Degree Research also have no students from 16 and under to 18.Look at the Graph 2, we can see that more than 118000 students including Domestic and Overseas choose to study Undergraduate and Postgraduate, which means that Universities can get more benefits when focusing on these two Broad Course Type.

Data cleaning and transformation

As we see at the factor disability having duplicated levels in dataframe a. I do some steps to eliminate the duplicated levels by transforming the values in disability, no disability and " No disability" to Disability and No-Disability. As the result, we can easily see that at the first row, the values in 3 duplicated levels come change to the values to Disability and No-Disability. At the second row, I drop out 3 unused levels, so that we can get just 2 levels in factor disability in dataframe a.

df$disability[df$disability == "disability"] <- "Disability"
df$disability[df$disability == "no disability"] <- "No-Disability"
df$disability[df$disability == "No disability"] <- "No-Disability"
dis.drop <- droplevels(df$disability)
summary(df$disability)
   disability    Disability No-Disability no disability No disability 
            0          5793        123174             0             0 
summary(dis.drop)
   Disability No-Disability 
         5793        123174

Why is Australia such a destination for disable students?

df$disability <- dis.drop

ggplot(df) +
geom_bar(aes(x= Year, fill= disability),position="dodge") +
   labs(title = "Number of Student in term of disability", x = "Year", y = "Number of Student") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  coord_flip()

Not only did Australia institutions increase the No-Disable student, but also they enhance the facilities to fit with the demand of Disable students. So through 2004 to 2017, the number of students of both rose from more than 7500 students to more than 11000 students. The graph answers the question above, Australian Institutions put great care on students with disabilitites having a wish to acquire knowledge to have a better life

Which is the best Univeristy in Australia?

df_known <- df[df$ATAR_Group != "Unknown",]
df_known$atar <- as.numeric(df_known$atar)

ggplot(data = df_known) +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes (x = Institution, y = atar, group = Institution)) +
  labs(title = "ATAR of each Insitution", x = "Institution", y = "ATAR") +
theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = rel(0.8))) +
  coord_flip()

At first, I saw that there is Unknown values in ATAR_Group, so I came up with the cleaning and transforming data. Then, I use ggplot with geom_bar to draw the new dataframe: df_known with x = Institution, y = atar (convert atar into numeric before plotting). As we can see in the graph, The University of Melbourne has the highest mean (68), and the atar doesnt vary much. So we can conclusion that The University of Melbourne is the best University in Austrlia due to the highest entry ATAR point.
